    <name>
      <text>3.4.5 (Monty Hall problem)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Suppose you are participating in a game show. There are three doors named \(A,B\) and \(C\), behind which are two goats and a car. You pick a door hoping for the car (say e.g. \(A\)). The game show host then examines the other two doors (doors \(B\) and \(C\)) and opens one with a goat behind it (if both doors have goats behind them the host picks randomly).</p>

<p>Given that you want to win the car should you stick with the original door you chose or should you switch to the other unopened door? (Enter the probabilities as a fraction).</p>

<p>The probability of winning the car if you do not switch is [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>

<p>The probability of winning the car if you switch is [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>

<p>Therefore in order to have the best chance of winning the car you should [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Surprisingly the odds are NOT 50-50. If you switch you have a \(2/3\) chance of winning the car. The reason why this is the case is slightly difficult to understand.</p>

<p>The reason that you have a better chance to win if you switch is because the host <i>curates</i> the remaining choices, so Monty opening one of the remaining doors doesn't change the odds. Let us consider each possibility in turn. </p>

