<p>Let us see what happens if you stick and if you switch for each scenario.</p>
<br/>
<p><b>Sticking:</b></p>

<p>You have picked door \(A\), you stay with door \(A\) and Monty opens a goat door. so in scenario 1 you would win the car. In the other two scenarios you would lose (as in these scenarios the car is not behind door \(A\)). Therefore this gives a probability of \(1/3\) for winning in all scenarios.</p>

<p><b>Switching:</b></p>

<p>You have picked door \(A\) and Monty opens a goat door. You then switch your choice. For scenario 1 you would lose but for the other two scenarios you would win. This means you have a \(2/3\) chance of winning in all scenarios.</p>

<p>The point here is that there are \(3\) doors and your original choice gives you odds of \(1/3\). There are two doors left, which have, together, a \(2/3\) chance of winning the car. The point is that Monty opening one of those doors doesnâ€™t change the odds.</p>]]></text>
